post_text:
Santa Fe Public Schools’ parents want their students to attend school remotely, based on responses to an SFPS request form. Results show that in 20 SFPS schools, a majority of parents want their students to learn remotely through the entire 2020-2021 school year.

Over 4,200 parents responded from 29 SFPS school sites. Each parent responded for up to four students. In total, the results show a strong preference for remote learning for the parents’ 5,100 students. For example, 24% of parents at Acequia Madre Elementary School want their children to learn remotely compared to 72% of parents at Ramirez Thomas Elementary School wanting remote.

“These results are a game changer for the District. Though we still need to contact parents we have not yet heard from, if the percentages hold, we may have to hit a reset button on our return-to-school staffing plans,” said Superintendent Dr. Veronica C. Garcia.

Click the link below to read the full release:

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1RA053c043dtJMPvELM2KuK3bzh7FMGvu/view?usp=sharing

Town Hall 1: Remote Learning for Pre-K through Grade 2
Tuesday, August 4th: 6:30pm -7:45 p.m.

Town Hall 2 Remote Learning for Grades 3 through 6
Wednesday, August 5th: 6:30-7:45 p.m.

Town Hall 3 Remote Learning for Middle and High School

Attention Parents and Families:

Remote Learning: Reimagined, Rebooted and Redesigned!
Please join the Superintendent and District Leadership for 3 Virtual Live Townhall Meetings to learn what will be new as we begin the school year in a remote learning model.

Go to sfps.info and connect to YouTube channel (https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCv_RRgkZ4kjfSSI1sGrqKFw/) to watch and participate live or at your convenience.

Town Hall 1: Remote Learning for Pre-K through Grade 2
Tuesday, August 4th: 6:30pm -7:45 p.m.

Town Hall 2 Remote Learning for Grades 3 through 6
Wednesday, August 5th: 6:30-7:45 p.m.

Town Hall 3 Remote Learning for Middle and High School
Thursday, August 6th: 6:30-7:45 p.m.

Stay connected...more town halls will be announced soon!

post_text:
Santa Fe Public Schools has compiled a list of FAQ's to help answer many of the questions regarding the 2020-2021 School Re-entry.

Please see the link below for the full list of FAQ's.

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1ZhD3ftvI1WvF8aw9nVKdus5Xsz5m_Xyg/view?usp=sharing

Q: When will SFPS schools begin to reopen?

A: SFPS will start school on August 20th in the full remote model. The Governor has ordered that all public schools begin in full remote through at least September 7th. Every student will have the option to attend school for the entire year in a remote model if this is their parent’s preference. All other students will continue the school year in the District’s hybrid model when the Governor lifts her order and COVID-19 transmission rates are below 1.05 for our region.

We are pleased to announce that SFPS will be expanding PreK services at Aspen Community School. If your child is 4 years old or will turn 4 before September 1st, you are eligible to apply to this free PreK program. Families will have to apply online at www.sfps.info. Seats will be offered on a first-come, first-serve basis. Spaces are limited, so we encourage you to apply as soon as possible. You can call Amy Casados for assistance at (505) 467-2547.

Nos complace anunciar que SFPS ampliará los servicios de preescolar en Aspen Community School. Si tu hijo tiene 4 anos de edad o los cumple antes del 1ero de septiembre puedes solicitar un lugar a este preescolar gratuito. Las familias deberán presentar su solicitud en línea en www.sfps.info. Los lugares se ofrecerán de acuerdo al día y hora en el que se reciba su solicitud. Los espacios son limitados, por lo que recomendamos solicite lo antes posible. Si necesita ayuda metiendo su solicitud puede llamar a Amy al (505) 467-2547.

Sadie, our Round 3 ninth grade winner, learned this song during distance learning. She said that her teacher has not been doing well and that online classes have been a struggle. She began working on this piece with him right before quarantine and chose to finish it by herself in dedication to him and hoping for his health. She says that she feels like this piece expresses her many different emotions during this time.

Fantastic job, Sadie!

So many people are struggling through this pandemic.

To help, the Santa Fe New Mexican has established The Empty Pantry Fund to provide some temporary assistance to residents of Santa Fe County who have been adversely impacted by the COVID 19 pandemic.

If you have been laid off, due to the COVID-19 pandemic, and are a resident of Santa Fe County, you can apply to receive a $200 grocery gift card.

And remember, SFPS offers free meals for ANY child, ages 1-18 on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays, 10:30 - 12:30 at the following locations: Capital High, Chaparral Elementary, El Camino Real Academy, Kearny Elementary, and Sweeney Elementary.

APPLY HERE: http://ow.ly/E0E650zU9O1

While the District is planning Graduation Celebrations, the individual school sites are also exploring ways to help recognize and encourage their graduating seniors.

One way they are doing this is through an "Adopt Our Seniors" program. Each school site has created a program donation through our wonderful partners, Dollars4Schools, to help celebrate and make it a memorable achievement for our students.

Your donation will allow for a momentous gift to be given to each graduating senior as they move into the new chapter of their lives.

Please help us celebrate our students and the resilient graduating class of 2020!

post_text:
Earlier this month, Mayor Alan Webber proclaimed May 2020 as "Santa Fe Bike Month".

The second week of May is traditionally Bike Week in Santa Fe. With the massive societal disruption caused by COVID-19, local organizers have grappled with how to maintain the spirit of the event, while respecting all-important social distancing requirements.

And so under the banner of #rideitoutsantafe, “Bike Month” was born!

Riding solo today, with the goal of riding together tomorrow, these events are designed to be ridden by oneself or with family “quaranteam” members. Head to https://www.santafebikeweek.com/ to find self-guided rides and activities for riders of all ages!

post_text: The Automotive Technology Pathway at ECO prepares students for entry level positions in the Auto Tech industry. Upon completion of the program, students will learn basic automotive problem solving skills involving mechanical, electrical, braking, suspension, and chassis systems.

post_text:
Last June, Early College Opportunities (ECO) hosted the first annual Go Kart Challenge Time Trials! This was the culmination of a two-week-long STEM summer camp for middle school students. During the camp, students in teams of five learned the science of racing through various project-based lessons and then applied that knowledge through the engineering process to build go karts.

The student teams raced their karts in a variety of time trial races. Teams earned points for their performance on the track, as well as in the classroom during the summer camp.

post_text:
Ms. Zapata, kindergarten teacher at Cesar Chavez, gave her students two challenges. The first was the Stone Challenge. They had to find some rocks with their family, then they needed to design a model on paper and paint the rocks.

The second was the Cooking Challenge. Being from Spain, she gave them a recipe called Torrijas (Spanish French Toast). Torrijas are made with slices of bread, covered in hot milk, mixed with sugar, cinnamon, orange and lemon peel. Then you cover them in beaten egg and you fry them in olive oil. Lastly, you cover them with sugar and cinnamon, if you wish, and they are ready to enjoy!

Yummy! 😋

Ms. Val teaches 2nd grade at Cesar Chavez Elementary School. About a month ago, she asked parents for feedback on how she can improve learning online. A parent suggested family projects, so she found a site with a 125 activities for kids during quarantine. Having a picnic was a suggestion on that site, but she decided to add fort building. Each week she has an optional project for kids and their families to do.

Great job, Ms. Val!

Santa Fe High held their first Senior Mentor Recognition Event this Saturday May 9, 2020.
This video is a highlight production that the Class of 2020 Senior Mentors put together to show current juniors at Santa Fe High what the program is all about.
SFHS Principal Carl Marano and Superintendent of Schools Dr. Veronica Garcia gave wonderful congratulatory speeches to the seniors along with the program president, Ms. Ciara Walsh.
The SFHS Senior Mentorship program has grown each year and is designed to commit and help incoming freshmen that may need extra support during their freshman year! To find out more about the program, please email Associate Principal Mr. Michael Granado at mgranado@sfps.k12.nm.us for more information.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qOXOhwIpb30

text:
While the District is planning Graduation Celebrations, the individual school sites are also exploring ways to help recognize and encourage their graduating seniors.

One way they are doing this is through an "Adopt Our Seniors" program. Each school site has created a program donation through our wonderful partners, Dollars4Schools, to help celebrate and make it a memorable achievement for our students.

Your donation will allow for a momentous gift to be given to each graduating senior as they move into the new chapter of their lives.

Please help us celebrate our students and the resilient graduating class of 2020!

GRADUATE TOGETHER 2020: The Class of 2020 is redefining high school graduation with a first-of-its-kind national ceremony. Graduate Together: America Honors the Class of 2020 will air simultaneously across ABC, CBS, FOX, and NBC, as well as a broad alliance of social media and streaming platforms. The one-hour primetime special airs on Saturday, May 16, and will honor the more than 3 million high school seniors across the country.

Artists, athletes, musicians, commencement speakers, influencers, and cultural icons will show their support with performances and messages featuring students, teachers, and their families from coast to coast.

There are many ways for New Mexicans to participate! The program is asking for students, teachers and families to share their stories, school spirit and graduation content. Check it out! The content you submit may be included in the TV program, on social media, or in PEOPLE Magazine.

Read about the celebration below -

https://www.graduatetogether2020.com/

post_text: Santa Fe Public Schools has opted in to participate in PED and ENGAGE New Mexico's effort which will utilize an experienced student outreach team that will work through multiple modes of communication to reach students who have disengaged during the transition to remote learning. This allows teachers to focus on teaching, reducing their fatigue, and provides preventative measures to students who are at a critical point in their education.

post_text:
Hello, SFPS family! Every so often, we will post communication directly from Superintendent Dr. Veronica C. Garcia. You'll know it's directly from her, when you see her initials (VCG) at the bottom of the post. Here's the first:

I am convening a meeting of the high school principals and district leadership to plan virtual activities for celebrating seniors during the month of May. We have to do all we can to ensure that our seniors feel celebrated and recognized for their accomplishments and for completing their high school graduation requirements under the worst of circumstances. This is a time of creating great memories and it's a nostalgic time. My heart is breaking for our seniors who have lost out on so much; we will do our best to do right by them.
-VCG

Within the school community, everyone is adjusting to new roles. Parents navigate new work situations. Educators find ways to continue learning beyond the classroom walls. What can students do?

STEMx is announcing the “Start a Smile” challenge, which will highlight the creativity and commitment of young people!

Students, your challenge is “Invent a Way to Help Someone Smile While in Isolation”. Entries are due May 1st, 2020 at 6 p.m. PST.

Submit a photo and short essay (150 words or less) of your solution and be sure to follow the student privacy rules of NO FACES or NAMES in your photo or essay. Your invention could be physical, digital, visual, audible, low tech, or high tech, but it should only use items found around your home.
Visit the link below for more information or to submit your entry.

https://www.futureengineers.org/startasmile

post_text: Santa Fe Public Schools would like to remind students and families that free behavioral health services via video conferencing and telephone calls are available to all SFPS families through our partnership with The Sky Center. Any family seeking support is encouraged to schedule an appointment. All services are free to members of our community with a child in the household between the ages of 0-23. If you are concerned about depression, anxiety, relationship conflict, suicidal behavior, or other behavioral health issues, please call The Sky Center at 505-473-6191. Thank you.

Congratulations to Peggy Cheeley, who was named the February Educational Support Professional of the Month!

Ms. Cheeley has served the Chaparral community for 7 years. She began as a Pre-K assistant, transitioned into the health assistant position and now serves as our school secretary. Peggy is exceptional at getting to know students and families. She can often be found speaking with students about making good choices and being responsible.

Thank you Ms. Cheeley for all that you do for our students, and thank you to our partners at NEA Santa Fe!

Dear Santa Fe Public Schools Staff, Students, Families and Community:

The ESC staff has been temporarily relocated due to a gas leak.

Office of the Superintendent, Student Services, General Council, Community Engagement, Assessment and Receptionist will be working out of BF Young, located at 1300 Camino Sierra Vista.

Data and Accountability, Business Services and Safety/Security will be working out of IT, located at 2516 Cerillos Road.

Please call (505) 467-2000 for any questions or to reach ESC staff, call their direct line and your call should be transferred. Please note, due to call volume there may be a delay in answering your call.

At this time, we anticipate the lottery results to be posted on our website no later than Monday, 2/23/20 by 8 pm.

We apologize for any inconvenience.

Milagro Middle School has been participating in a unique exploration of the universe as part of the Santa Fe Institute’s Interplanetary Festival.(I=)UNIVERSE is a STEMarts Lab production in collaboration with multiple departments at SFPS, including Art, Science, Technology, and Native American Student Services. It offers an intensive, hands-on workshop that includes digital technology, particle physics, and Native-Western science connections. The students have been working with artists, an astrophysicist from Los Alamos National Labs, and have had virtual visits with experts in Geneva and Austria.

You can see the students work at the Innovation EXPO: Full STEAM ahead! on February 13th, 2020. Their work will be projected on the side of the Santa Fe Convention Center after dark.

SFPS has announced that the school calendar for the 2020-2021 school year will not feature any mandatory additional instructional days. The beginning of the school year for students will be August 17th and the last day of school will be May 26th.

The district will offer entirely voluntary Extended Learning and K-5(8) Plus programs, pending funding from the New Mexico Public Education Department. These programs will only be offered at locations where parent and teacher interest warrants. The specific school sites will be announced at a later date.

On January 29th, Superintendent Dr. Veronica C. Garcia recognized the January Teacher and ESP (Educational Support Professional) of the Month.

This month's teacher is Ed Gorman at El Camino Real Academy, who has been a part of the Agua Fria/El Camino Real Academy community for 18 years.

The ESP of the Month is Christine Ortega, secretary at Milagro Middle. She goes beyond her duties by organizing potlucks, PTO's and the holiday bazaar.

Congratulations to both for their exceptional work!

Congratulations Bryson, keep up the great work!

shared_text:
City of Santa Fe
December 10, 2019 at 5:19 PM ·

ESD Goes to Atalaya Elementary
We want to teach them while they're still young and curious that Recycling is the right thing to do!

Last week, a team from the Environmental Services Division visited with Ms. Gibb’s Pre-K class at Atalaya Elementary School. Recycling Lead Driver Abran Sanchez answered questions about where the recycling goes and how the truck works. Then, the class watched as Abe and Operations Manager Eric Lucero demonstrated the automated cart collection system. Thank you to Ms. Gibbs and class for a great visit, and thank you for recycling, Santa Fe!
#recyclerightsantafe #Schools

post_text:
Computer Science Education Week is Dec. 9-13th and the Kickoff event is being livestreamed from New Mexico!
Watch the #CSEdWeek live stream, Dec. 9th 10-11am
Code.org and the Computer Science Teachers Association (CSTA) are partnering with the New Mexico Computer Science Alliance to kick off Computer Science Education Week (CSEdWeek) at the Santa Fe Indian School on December 9th. We'll celebrate the 10th year of CSEdWeek and all the people who make this movement so special.

The kick-off event will feature remarks from Hadi Partovi, CEO of Code.org, and Jake Baskin, Executive Director of the CSTA, as well as a special panel discussion around this year's Hour of Code theme, CS for Good. It will also feature an awards ceremony for this year's Champions of Computer Science.

The livestream starts at 10am Mountain Time (9:00am PT / 12:00pm ET) on Monday, December 9th. You can watch on the CSEdWeek Facebook page or Code.org's YouTube channel. #sfps #sfpsdistrict

Due to inclement weather over the last couple of weeks, SFPS cancelled our Basic Math Tutor Preparation training workshop which was originally scheduled for November 21, 2019.

We have determined a new date for the workshop, which will be Wednesday, January 15, 2020 from 2- 5 PM at the BF Young Professional Center. This training is free and available to anyone in the community who would like to participate.

You can register for the Basic Math Tutor Preparation training by filling out this form and selecting the RESCHEDULED- Basic Math Tutor Preparation option: https://forms.gle/gfvBWD1ousWG8YYY6

For more information about the training program, please visit our website at https://www.sfps.info/departments/volunteering___s_f_p_s/volunteer_training_program. #sfps #sfpsdistrict

post_text: Happy Veterans Day! SFHS NJROTC and school staff hosted Santa Fe veterans who have served in the United States Armed Forces with a breakfast and ceremony to show appreciation for all those who have served our country. The day began with a dedication of facility improvements at the NJROTC building, followed by breakfast, speeches by staff and students, including music by members of SFHS' choir. The morning was capped off with NJROTC students' participation in the Santa Fe Veterans Day Parade through downtown. Thank you veterans, for your service to our country. #sfps #sfpsdistrict
